    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-07-09T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-07-09T08:00:00-05:00" n="258"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d258">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.00/7–948: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Political Adviser for Germany</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MRD1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murphy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Frankfurt</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-07-09T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 9, 1948—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>39. Eyes Only. Remytel 38, July 9<note n="1" xml:id="d258fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>.</note> concerning <gloss target="#t_SPD1"
                        >SPD</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_CDU1">CDU</gloss> meetings July 7.</p>
                <p>Military Government circles have privately advised Germans to accept Frankfurt
                    proposals because.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>If not they will only get less.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>They should frankly recognize split of Germany as fact.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>They should not become involved in legal fantasy of “sovereignty”.
                        Regardless what Germans call new government document, administrative
                        statute, etc., it will be translated into English as “constitution”.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Murphy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
